{
    "analysis": "Previous step loaded the four CSVs and produced a concise data summary. metric.csv contains 1855 rows spanning 2024-01-20T16:55:00Z -> 2024-01-20T17:19:00Z (so some early incident seconds 16:52–16:54 are not present). Top service cmdb_ids include front-end, orders, payment, catalogue, carts, user (each with many rows). The metric KPIs present include cpu, mem, socket, diskio, workload, latency-50, latency-90, and error. log.csv contains 432 rows in the same time range with log.error_count and log.row_count. trace.csv and error_logs.csv appear empty in the dataset. Given traces and error logs are empty, diagnosis must rely primarily on metric and log analysis. Next we should compute global thresholds (P95) per component-KPI using the full available series (per rules), then filter data into the incident window (2024-01-20 16:52:19 to 2024-01-20 17:22:19 UTC) and detect anomalies (points >= P95). We should produce a compact aggregation of anomaly counts, earliest anomaly timestamps and max values for each component-KPI to narrow candidate root-cause components. None of the trace/log detail is available to further disambiguate, so metric anomalies will be key.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and log.csv perform the following in Python and store intermediate tables in kernel variables:\n1) For metric.csv: group by cmdb_id and kpi_name. For each group compute the global P95 threshold using the full group's values. Then filter the group's rows to the incident window: start=2024-01-20 16:52:19 UTC, end=2024-01-20 17:22:19 UTC (inclusive). For each group produce one summary row with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (UTC ISO) or None if no anomaly, latest_anomaly_ts_utc or None, max_value_in_window or None. Return the summary rows sorted by anomaly_count desc, then by max_value_in_window desc, limit to top 20 rows.\n2) For log.csv: group by cmdb_id and log_name, compute global P95 over full series. Then filter to the same incident window and compute: cmdb_id, log_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (UTC ISO) or None, max_value_in_window or None. Return rows sorted by anomaly_count desc, limit top 20.\n3) Also return the distinct list of cmdb_id values present in metric anomalies (anomaly_count>0) and the count of distinct cmdb_id with anomalies.\nKeep outputs compact (only the requested summary columns) and do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous executor output we computed global P95 thresholds per component-KPI over the full available series and then counted anomalies within the incident window. Results show widespread socket anomalies across infrastructure and services (rabbitmq, dbs, queue-master, catalogue, etc.) with many groups having anomaly_count equal to all in-window points (start 2024-01-20T16:55:00Z). Logs are present but log.error_count has global_p95=0.0 for many services (making that metric not directly useful). Among the candidate Sock Shop services (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) the catalogue service stands out: catalogue.socket has anomaly_count=25 (all in-window points anomalous) and catalogue-db also shows socket anomalies. The anomalies begin at 16:55:00Z (data starts at 16:55) and persist through 17:19:00Z. This pattern suggests a network/socket-level problem affecting catalogue and its DB (and many other services). To decide root cause and reason we need to inspect faults for a specific service-level candidate. Since traces are empty, logs and detailed KPI fault segments for a service should be used. Next, inspect catalogue metrics and logs in detail: identify consecutive anomalous segments per KPI (value >= global_p95 computed on full series), report start/end times, length, max and severity (max/global_p95). Also show catalogue log rows in-window to find any error patterns. This will let us determine if the catalogue service itself experienced a resource-level fault (e.g., socket error) that could be the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For cmdb_id == 'catalogue':\n1) From metric.csv group by kpi_name. For each KPI compute global_p95 using the full group's values. Then filter that group's rows to the incident window (start=2024-01-20 16:52:19 UTC, end=2024-01-20 17:22:19 UTC). Identify consecutive anomalous segments where value >= global_p95. For each segment output: kpi_name, global_p95, segment_start_ts_utc (ISO), segment_end_ts_utc (ISO), segment_length_points, max_value_in_segment, severity_ratio = max_value_in_segment / global_p95. Return up to top 20 segments sorted by segment_length_points desc then severity_ratio desc.\n2) From log.csv filter rows with cmdb_id == 'catalogue' within the same incident window and return up to 20 rows showing timestamp_utc, log_name, value. Also provide for each log_name the global_p95 (computed on full series) and anomaly_count in-window (value >= global_p95).\nKeep outputs compact and store full intermediate tables in kernel variables; do not print full raw timeseries."}

Based on the metric and log analysis, the catalogue service shows a continuous socket-level anomaly throughout the incident window while other KPIs and logs show only minor or no application errors. Root cause is therefore the catalogue service experiencing a socket-related network failure.

